<p>I have 3 tables:</p>  <p><strong>users</strong>:</p>  <pre><code>id  name 1   Jack 2   Vasya 3   John 4   Robert 5   Dmitry 6   Dylan </code></pre>  <p><strong>cities</strong>:</p>  <pre><code>id  city 1   London 2   Kyiv 3   New-York 4   Chicago 5   Moscow 6   Dubai </code></pre>  <p><strong>users_cities</strong>:</p>  <pre><code>user_id city_id 1       1 3       1 5       6 2       3 4       5 6       6 </code></pre>  <p>I need to select users with Jack in London by Jack's id(users.id = 1) or users in Dubai with Dmitry(users.id = 5) using JOIN. How could I do it?</p>  <p>What I have tried:</p>  <pre><code>SELECT `u`.`username`, `uc`.`city_id` FROM `users` as `u`     INNER JOIN `users_cities` as `uc` ON `u`.`id` = `uc`.`user_id`     INNER JOIN `users_cities` as `uc1` ON `uc1`.`city_id` = `uc`.`city_id` WHERE `u`.`id` = 1 </code></pre>  <p>It returns:</p>  <pre><code>username    city_id Jack        1 Jack        1 </code></pre>